{"questionId":"27290","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>An environmental scientist is asked by a river authority to model the effect of a leak from a power plant on the mercury levels in a local river. The variable <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> measures the concentration of mercury in micrograms per litre.</p>\n<p>The situation is modelled using the second order differential equation</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mtext>d</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>\n<p>where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;is the time measured in days since the leak started. It is known that when&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the eigenvalues of the system of coupled first order equations given in part (a).</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>the relevant matrix is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>1</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math>&nbsp;is also possible.</p>\n<p><br>(this has characteristic equation)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>λ</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>λ</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>λ</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27290","referenceCode":"22M.2.AHL.TZ2.7b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the eigenvalues of the system of coupled first order equations given in part (a).","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.15—Eigenvalues and eigenvectors"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}